<br>
Plato stated no less than 3 times during his accounts of Atlantis that the legend was completely true. He never made up a civilisation before or afterwards. Fictional stories always revolved around real people and events. I'm convinced he was convinced of its authenticity. He claimed the original source to be Egypt and his ancestor who supposedly obtained the tale was a mythic figure in greece. He wrote Athenian law. To have deliberately insulted his own blood with a made up tale would have been an unthinkable sin to such an honourable philosopher as Plato. Even Aristotle his student didn't believe him though. Tell me if I've mixed the names around. My greek history is a little rusty. The Egyptians had explained that Greece was very young. That they knew nothing. That the World had been destroyed and recreated many times over but some parts had weathered better than others and Egypt was such a place. Modern research seems to back up the idea of global catastrophes in the ancient past.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=captainbeowulf>CaptainBeowulf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/12/03 4:39 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=24.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Ancient Civilizations</span><hr size=1> I agree that moderns tend to view their ancestors as being a bunch of superstitious primitives.  Many of their stories are put down to &quot;myth&quot;.  Yet these people often did try to describe, accurately, what they knew - surprisingly seldom were they just making it up.  An example of this is the city of Troy.  Almost all academics agreed that Troy was just a myth, a made-up setting for a heroic saga devised for cultural purposes.  Then Troy is discovered, exactly where they said it would be, with evidence of a war at the time they said there was a war.  If there hadn't been a small group of people quite determined to find it, Troy could easily have gone unnoticed still today - an entire city hidden by only a few thousand years.<br>
<br>
People like Thor Hayerdahl have demonstrated that early peoples could have crossed the oceans in primitive craft made out of reeds.  Yet we know that people even in a few thousand years ago had better technology than that - the Egyptians, some proto-Celtic and proto-Germanic tribes, early Greeks and Phoenicians and others were able to build sturdier wooden craft.<br>
<br>
Some researchers claim to have found evidence of ancient, if sporadic, worldwide trade.  Some claim that there is evidence of south American cocoa in at least one Egyptian sarcophagous.  Given that people had the theoretical technology to cross oceans I wouldn't be surprised if there was sporadic contact between civilizations.<br>
<br>
Also consider that vast areas of the world, both then and now, speak Indo-European languages.  Well-attested languages like Latin, ancient Greek, Sanscrit, Persian, early Germanic languages (Old English, Old High German, Old Low German, and Norse), as well as what written scraps of Hittite, Old Slavonic and early Celtic, are all obviously based on a single parent language.  Although other language groups exist in western and central Eurasia, Indo-European is the dominant linguistic form from Ireland to India.  Such a universal language could suggest a very wide sphere of cultural and political interaction which broke down at some point, leading to the splintering of the parent language into sub-languages (Indo-European is known to have been imported into some areas by armies based around chariot warefare between 3000 to 5000 years ago, yet even before that time it appears likely that the linguistic group was widespread).<br>
<br>
People a few thousand years ago were also highly interested in astronomy.  Stonehenge is a very good observatory, and it is not unique in its design - very similar &quot;observatories&quot; appear not only throughout western Europe, but there are a few examples even in Egypt, Eastern Europe and the Middle East.  Sites in Britain, Ireland and France simply draw attention because they are the largest and most ostentatious of their kind.  These systems would have allowed ancients to calculate orbital movements of celestial bodies and determine the exact length of the year, including the need to have &quot;leap years&quot;, and so establish both a sense of time and ability to navigate.  Such knowledge of navigation by stars may have allowed them to navigate the oceans beyond sight of land with confidence.  Certainly the Greeks, Egyptians and Romans knew that the world was round - they were able to do calculations to prove it.<br>
<br>
Finally, more or less anatomically &quot;modern&quot; humans have existed for about 100 000 years.  I find the idea that settled civilization began only 10 000 years ago to be somewhat odd.<br>
<br>
What could have ended more ancient civilizations?  A number have speculated on the possibility of an asteroid hitting the earth.  There is some circumstancial evidence in terms of dust layers in the ground and also a major crater in Iraq that a few large asteroids could have hit a few thousand years ago - bigger than Tunguska but not dinosaur-killers.  Nonetheless, you'd think that the evidence of any really major impact would still be around.  Another thing to consider is that 10 000 years ago the last ice age was just ending.  The several dozen thousand years before that would have been characterized by a lot of environmental change - rise of sea levels and massive flooding, formerly fertile areas becoming deserts, entire species going extinct or changing their migration patterns.  All of this would massively disrupt any establish economic patterns, quite possibly to the point of causing previously wealthy civilizations to collapse.  Evidence of their existence could easily be in places that we're just not looking at very hard - some people believe that there are remains of an ancient city in the ocean off Japan, and there are vast areas of seafloor that we haven't examined yet.<br>
<br>
Literacy in Europe was very nearly lost at the end of the Roman Empire - most of what we have of the &quot;classics&quot; today was transcribed either in a handful of monastaries or by a few Islamic scholars (Islamic copies of European writings mostly made their way back into Europe during the Crusades and through Spain).  If climate change had displaced all the monastaries and there was no other neighbouring literate civilization to transcribe anything, it's quite possible that a written language could have been completely lost.<br>
<br>
For all these reasons I believe that much, perhaps most, of our history is still unknown to us.  As others have said here, you'd think that an advanced society would leave some artifacts that we would find, but if plastics and metals had had tens of thousands of years to disintegrate, or were buried under the seafloor where we've had no reason to go drilling, there is a slight possibility (I emphasize slight) that a surprisingly advanced civilization could have existed in the past - possibly the template for Plato's Atlantis.<br>
<br>
As for aliens visiting the earth in the past?  If there are creatures out there who don't mind interstellar flights that take several decades (I'm assuming that FTL travel is impossible but near-light speed travel is achievable) then sure, why not?  But if they did every drop by, they didn't leave any decent evidence that they did so - at least none that we have.  Someone above stated that we will probably never know - to this I would respond that actually, if we push on and develop real deep space flight capabilities, we quite possibly will know... since we'll eventually find the kin of our ancient visitors!<br>
<br>
Sorry for writing a lecture here - but this stuff kind of interests me. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 872<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/12/03 4:23 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=24.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Ancient Civilizations</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Finally, more or less anatomically &quot;modern&quot; humans have existed for about 100 000 years. I find the idea that settled civilization began only 10 000 years ago to be somewhat odd.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
