<br>
I remember seeing aerial footage of the Amazon rainforest on the discovery channel, in which they were showing that vast areas of the Amazon had apparently been systematically channelized with dykes and dams and farmed.  The evidence looked very good, although one should not believe everything that one sees on the discovery channel (or any TV channel for that matter), so I'm not saying that this is definitive.  However, assuming that you were using a coastal rainforest for something like rice paddies - a rise in the water table of even 50cm could disrupt your agricultural system badly.<br>
<br>
Even an *advanced* civilization like ours has massive coastal clusters - which is what a lot of the hype about global warming today is about.  A rise of a few meters in the sea level could inundate large areas of Boston, New York, Los Angeles, Rotterdam, Hamburg, London, etc. etc.<br>
<br>
The first spikes in the sea level disrupt civilization over a period of several decades, then the following increases end up covering the ruins with up to 50 meters of water over the next few thousand years.  It is impossible for civilization to re-establish the standard coastal settlement pattern because the sea level keeps rising.  People are forced inland and ocean and river trade (the fastest and cheapest way of moving until you have internal combustion engines for wheeled land vehicles, or aircraft) languish.  No one wants to build a harbour because it will be gone in 30 years, and without any harbours you don't build many ships (you still build a few primitive Thor Hayerdahl type things, but no gallions).<br>
<br>
As for civilization during the stable period of the ice age's furthest extent, there would still have been plenty of temperate land similar to that which supported classical civilizations - just closer to the equator.  The ice age would certainly not have made it impossible to support a major civilization.  For instance, there's good evidence that during the last ice age the Sahara desert was a fertile savannah, with grass, trees, animal herds etc.  Large areas of it could have been farmed.  As the world grew warmer it turned into a vast unlivable barrier.  This would be another factor which could destroy civilizations - even the areas which weren't flooded would have suffered drastic climate change, forcing you to move on to the new temperate lands which had before been covered by glaciers. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 875<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/13/03 7:43 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=24.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Agriculture</span><hr size=1> I remember reading a half-baked hypothesis that our species didn't achieve conscious self-awareness until about 10,000 years ago.  Although I don't believe that hypothesis, it's possible that the population was just too small and that no had given thought or the ability to motivate people to undertake big time, irrigated farming until about 10,000 years ago.  A population that lives soley on what they find in nature is necessarily restricted to having small populations.  I believe the sudden emergence of civilizations as we know them came ab