Yes.......but. This interglacial period we are living in which has lasted about 12,000 years (10,000 BC so easy to confuse) isn't the first. So far eleven have been mapped throughout the Ice Age. Humans didn't exist before the Ice Age so there is thought to be a relationship between the arrival of it and human evolution. You would have heard about the Savannah Hypothesis with its forest growth receding to grasslands and consequently forcing apes to survive on the open plain. Each of these shortlived heatwaves were similar to today. Roughly identical duration averaging from 8,000 to 12,000 years. Ours must be close to finishing as it is already close to if not already setting a record. Some scholars have even suggested it is already over but being kept at bay by greenhouse gases warming the Earth and countering it. Unfortunately, if this is the case then the eventual arrival of glacier sheets will happen more swiftly when it actually happens. Past interglacial endings have taken place in under a year so the World could get cold very suddenly. A very brief return is thought to have occured during what is commonly referred to as the Dark Ages. Both European and Chinese literature of the period relate 4 hour days and famines. It lasted only a century or two which is strange. Mind you Earthquakes often have precursor tremors.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=captainbeowulf>CaptainBeowulf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 8<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/15/03 4:11 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=24.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Ice Ages</span><hr size=1> Good points - things can get cold very quickly, as well as hot very quickly.<br>
<br>
What effect would glaciation have on archeaological remains of previous interglacial civilizations?  Up to 2km thick ice sheets (if I remember correctly) scouring the landscape like giant, slow-moving rivers - ruins could easily be crushed into rubble and then ridistributed over thousands of square kilometres of land.<br>
<br>
Another thought occured to me: what if ice ages were often ended by a massive asteroid impact?  If an asteroid were to strike in the northern or southern hemispheres, where the ice sheets are kilometres thick, is it possible that the impact crater would be made only in the ice and not penetrate to the ground beneath, and, since the ice would melt, therefore leave no evidence?  Furthermore, although there is grit and boulders (erratics) in some glacial ice, would an impact in ice fail to kick up much dust, thus causing no &quot;nuclear winter&quot; and leaving no evidence of a soot layer in ground borings?  Would such an impact simply release massive heat on a planetary scale, enough to readjust the jetstream and ocean currents, melt enough of the ice to alter the planet's albido, and set the planet on a warming trend?<br>
<br>
It would be cool if someone could do some physics on how the tensile and thermal properties of ice would withstand a &quot;plannet killer&quot; impact to get an idea of whether this theory is out to lunch or not.  Unfortunately, I don't know the specific figures to do this, nor am I sure how to set the math up for it, and I don't have the time to do the research - but if someone more informed in these details wants to do some quick calculations to see whether a &quot;no crater, no soot&quot; please jump in. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 3404<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/15/03 10:03 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=24.topic&index=14>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2001/05/images/021011_nuclear.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Ice Ages</span><hr size=1> My brain is swimming.<br>
