I don't know. I suspect big Asteroids must have struck during glacial periods. More than have done interglacially for sure. Dionosaur killers are thought to be really rare but we might get fairly hefty collisions every hundred thousand years or so. I'll look up the timescales. A geologist would know I expect. Another consideration is polar shift. Antarctica was once covered in jungle. Could there be cities down there under the ice. Ground to pulp maybe. I recall being told that man was still at the Australopithecine stage when Antarctica froze so maybe not. They didn't even have decent flint scrapers at that point.<br>
<br>
If some remenant of advanced pre-historical settlement were to survive into the present era, where would it most likely be? At the top of a mountain? Buried under hundreds of metres of mud offshore? Nowhere? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=captainbeowulf>CaptainBeowulf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 9<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/15/03 7:25 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=24.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Decay of Artifacts</span><hr size=1> Good call - comparing the timescales of interglacial periods with the predicted frequency of large collisions is the first step to seeing whether the idea makes sense.<br>
<br>
As for where ruins would be, I'll think out loud some more - excuse me if I carry on too long.  Earlier in this discussion you wrote:<br>
<br>
&quot;It's true that if civilisation were to end today there would be no trace of our having existed after tens of thousands of years. A big asteroid would wipe out almost everything in seconds. Even plastic disintegrates in about 10,000 years.&quot;<br>
<br>
It would be interesting to study the decay rates of materials commonly used by advanced civilizations under different conditions.  Materials buried in heavy sediments where things like oxidizing agents can't reach them in large quantaties would decay at different rates than stuff on the surface.  How long could various plastics, stainless steel, (maybe even carbon nanotube based materials?!!) survive under various conditions?  Basic iron, bronze and copper would likely go pretty quickly, but carved granite architecture should survive a very long time.<br>
<br>
If we assume that they mined material like we do, then collapsed mineshafts are probably the best bet for surviving artifacts.  However, all of their mineshafts may have been in the continental shelves, now covered by ocean, since the inland highlands would have been glaciated and difficult to get at.<br>
<br>
It brings us back to the same problem: ruins are likely in formerly coastal areas, which means that they are now underwater, and very likely covered by sediments washed onto the continental shelves by large rivers.  Thus sonar and even satellites are unlikely to pick up very much except seabed; we need to see &quot;through&quot; the upper layers of seabed to see if there is anything lurking on the continental shelves.<br>
<br>
Is there some sort of imaging satellite we could dream up and propose which may be able to &quot;shine&quot; radio waves or something similar through seawater and the upper levels of sea sediment to &quot;map&quot; the deeper layers of terrain?  It would be a nice project to add to the first launch manifest of the Liberty Ship <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
I still suspect that anything glaciers could have reached would be ground into nothingness.<br>
<br>
We're also incipiently discussing two scenarios here: we should clarify the possibilities.  The first is that civilization arose during interglacial periods, and that humanity then barely survived glaciations, while the other is that civilization arose during the last glaciation in temperate coastal areas and was then flooded out by deglaciation.<br>
<br>
These two scenarios can easily be combined into a third: civilization arose in the last interglacial period, then got &quot;frozen out&quot;, reestablished itself in coastal areas, then got floode out, then reestablished itself again in our &quot;classical age&quot;.  This cycle may have happened a few times.  All of this would explain why the Egyptians would have mentioned the earth being &quot;remade&quot; a number of times, of which the Greeks are unaware.<br>
<br>
The more I think about this, the more it make sense to me in terms of the Atlantis myth:  Atlantis was supposedly consumed under the oceans, but instead of being a &quot;lost continent&quot; or &quot;lost island&quot;, it was simply civilization(s) on the flooded coastal areas of existing continents.<br>
<br>
If glaciations are ended by an asteroid impact, it would explain the description of fire and brimstone along with massive floods destroying Atlantis: not a volcanic explosion causing a tsunami, but a huge fireball dropping from the sky and sending out not only shockwaves and heatwaves but also torrents of meltwater. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tim1965>Tim1965</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 125<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/16/03 10:53 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=24.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Decay of Artifacts</span><hr size=1> The archeological evidence that has been found shows that<br>
the minoan empire of Thera in the mediterrrean sea<br>
was the most likley source of the Atlantis legend.<br>
Tim<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=captainbeowulf>CaptainBeowulf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 14<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/17/03 12:26 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=24.topic&index=17>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Thera</span><hr size=1> That's one theory - but people are far from agreed on it.  Thera definitely was a major civilization, and its end also resembles the Atlantis story - the volcano exploding, thus creating massive waves.  Thus you get the fire, brimstone, and flooding in the tale.  However, Thera doesn't match Plato's description either in terms of the location (&quot;beyond the pillars of Hercules ie. in the Atlantic west of Gibraltar).  We can assume that Plato was out to lunch in his description, but if we had gone on assuming that Homer was making stuff up we might never have found Troy.  Therefore the possibility remains that Plato may have actually been speaking about a region now (a) underwater on the continental shelf, (b) in western Europe or (c) the African coastline, or (d) in South America. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 919<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/18/03 6:13 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=24.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Thera</span><hr size=1> Good point about the Troy connection.  I'm more open minded now that perhaps there really was some lost island civilization called Atlantis.  Considering how advanced Minoa was for its time, it wouldn't surprise me if that might have been the culture being referred to as Atlantis.  I think the main obstancle that keep Atlantis from being seriously considered is the reputation that some people have assigned to it as being some super technological civilization that surpassed even our own.  Whenever I hear Atlantis being mentioned I seem to automatically reject it because of the reason just mentioned.    <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=captainbeowulf>CaptainBeowulf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 16<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/19/03 2:30 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=24.topic&index=19>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Thera, Atlantis etc.</span><hr size=1> You're absolutely right about the problem with Atlantis - I myself made some comments above about super-advanced technologies, but they are joking comments.<br>
<br>
I actually think that &quot;Atlantis&quot; is probably a conflation of a few different civilizations into one story (historically this is common - many myths are composites of different events and people).  To make the point in any detail I'd have to quote several different historical and quasi-historical (but still not lunatic fringe) articles, but here are the basics:<br>
<br>
1.  Plato's description is influenced by contemporary events, including the destruction of a city-state called Helike by a seismic sea wave and earthquakes which altered the course of wars in Greece.<br>
2.  Thera/Minoa is an older influence on the story, having come to an end in a similar way, and is probably the &quot;Atlantis&quot; that was the enemy of &quot;Ancient Athens&quot;.<br>
3.  The basis or grain of truth in the story is a society which existed on the continental shelf of western Europe during the last major glaciation.  Because of the lower sea levels, the distance to travel across the north Atlantic was shorter and the islands (Iceland, Greenland) were larger and there were more of them.  Thus a coastal trade route across to the Americas reaching down to south America could be established.  Other trade links between the continents are also feasible.  A relatively quick rise in sea level disrupted the areas of coastal trade badly enough that the societies didn't reestablish themselves inland, and thus all the artifacts are underwater.  The higher water levels also made the gaps between continents too large to cross, so societies turned inward.<br>
<br>
Unfortunately one cannot publish seriously on the topic of Atlantis, because if one does one gets labelled as a crank.  Oh well, guess the result isn't too different from advocating nuclear space flight when Greenpeace and friends get on your case <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :rolleyes --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/eyes.gif ALT=":rolleyes"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
No super-technologies or aliens were needed to facilitate intercontinental travel or construction of major artifacts like stonehenge... just coastal and island-hopping trade routes combined with large populations in temperate coastal plains.<br>
<br>
The cool &quot;what if&quot; that emerges from this is what if human civilization had progressed in a linear improvement pattern, instead of reversing course into wandering tribes repeatedly?  Where would we be now?  This is largely the same as the what if Alexander the Great or the Roman Empire still ruled - but giving us an extra several thousand years to develop... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nebobgrenville>nebobgrenville</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://my.oregonstate.edu/courses/1/NE_114_X001_F2002/uploads/homepage/_1060577_1/triga.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 246<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/19/03 2:22 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=24.topic&index=20>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>   Thera, Atlantis etc.</span><hr size=1> The problem with the Minoans being Atlantis is that they bare already recorded in Greek myth, they were never forgotten. The tales of Minos and bull related Minotaurs are likely a relic of the bull-obsessed Minoans.<br>
<br>
Plato was not known for making stories up, but that does not mean that the legend was passed down perfectly. There are several questionable aspects to his story. First of all he claims that his ancestor Solon heard it in Egypt. The Egyptians thought of themselves as the origonaters of civilization, viewing others in a dim light. They rarely if ever recorded forign history. The claim that they told a story about a more advanced civilization before their time (how could they record events before their time anyways?) is shakey at best. It is known from achiological digs that Athans has only been inhabited for a few thousand years, far too short for it to be in the picture around 9600 BC.<br>
<br>
This does not mean that he lied however. I remember reading a good theory based on the fact that the tale origonated from an Anatolian legend of the city of Tantalus. Solon did visit ANatolia to meet with the Lydian King, an ocation which included an exchange of tales. Tantalis was founded by the children of Tantalus, essentaily a Lydian version of Atlas, Plato's founder of Atlantis. The city eventually fell from favor with its patron, who like Atlas was condemned to hold up the sky, and it was destroyed by earthquakes and drowned benieth a lake. The two tales are surprisingly similar. The origonal home for Atlas was Anatolia, he was leter banished to the West. As such it would be understandible that Plato in recordeing an orally passed down legend placed the city far out in the West. It is similaerly believible that the story got embelished over the generations glorifying Athens. <p>&quot;If,&quot; he wispered, &quot;if we could only pick that lock....&quot; - , THE WORLD SET FREE</p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top">  Page  <b>1</b> <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showMessageRange?topicID=24.topic&start=21&stop=29>2</a> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showPrevMessage?topicID=24.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showNextMessage?topicID=24.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a self href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=24.topic&index=20><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/addreply3.jpg border=0 alt="Add Reply"></a> </td></tr></table><br><table width=95% border=0><td valign="top"> <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.emailToFriend?topicID=24.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/image/email.gif border=0 alt="Email This To a Friend"> Email This To a Friend</a><br> <a hr